BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Scarlett (Rong) He PhD Completion Seminar
DTSTART:20260218T110000
DTEND:20260218T120000
DESCRIPTION:Presenter:Scarlett (Rong) He\n\nSupervisors:David Pitt\, Shuan
 ming Li\, Zhuo Jin (Macquarie Business School)\n\nTitle:Data-Driven Actuar
 ial Modelling of Cyber Risk: Frequency\, Severity\, and Insurance Pricing\
 n\nDay/Time:Wednesday 18 February 2026\, 11am - 12pm Australian Eastern Da
 ylight Time Time (AEDT)\n\nVenue:FBE-304\n\nZoom Link:https://unimelb.zoom
 .us/j/89762547188?pwd=5D8zMxbyg70viHWcZSaVNaRrnaxRZK.1(Password: 414939)\n
 \nAbstract:\n\nThis thesis investigates cyber risk through an integrated f
 ramework that links loss occurrence\, loss severity\, and insurance decisi
 on making under realistic information availability situations. Aninterdisc
 iplinary survey first synthesises existing research across fields includin
 g computer science\, business and economics\, and actuarial studies\, high
 lighting fragmentation in current approaches and motivating the need for u
 nified modelling frameworks.\n\nBuilding on these insights\, cyber loss fr
 equency is reinterpreted through an epidemic lens that captures temporal a
 nd feature dependent propagation dynamics\, while loss severity is studied
  using both distributional approaches and modern machine learning and deep
  learning methods\, taking into consideration that incident-specific chara
 cteristics are unobservable at the time of underwriting. Finally\, predict
 ive outputs are embedded into a reinforcement learning framework that expl
 ores deductible and coverage limit design under alternative pricing settin
 gs. The results from these studies demonstrate that epidemic-informed freq
 uency models improve incident count prediction\, that predicted incident t
 ypes can serve as an informative feature with only marginal loss of accura
 cy in severity prediction\, and that these predictive components can be ma
 pped into practical insurance contract design under different pricing obje
 ctives through a reinforcement learning module.\n\nOverall\, the thesis en
 riches actuarial modelling of cyber risk by drawing on epidemic processes 
 to accommodate cyber risk propagation and by bridging predictive analysis 
 and insurance decision making under the practical constraints of cyber ins
 urance markets
URL:https://fbe.unimelb.edu.au/economics/events/seminars/scarlett-rong-he-
 phd-completion-seminar
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Macroeconomics Seminar Series - Terry Cheung (Academia Sinica)
DTSTART:20260219T120000
DTEND:20260219T131500
DESCRIPTION:Title: From Slavery to Stagnation: Agricultural Technology and
  Structural Transformation in the US South\n\nAbstract: This paper examine
 s how the legacy of American slavery shaped agricultural mechanization and
  structural transformation in the U.S. South. Using county-level data\, we
  document that areas with higher enslaved ratios in 1860 experienced persi
 stently lower farm wages\, slower tractor adoption\, and weaker subsequent
  manufacturing growth. Instrumental-variable evidence indicates that discr
 iminatory labor-market institutions suppressed wages and reduced incentive
 s to adopt labor-saving technology. We then build and calibrate a county-l
 evel quantitative model that maps enslaved concentration into an agricultu
 ral wage wedge and incorporates tractor-embodied technological progress. O
 ur model-based decomposition shows that changes in wage suppression alone 
 account for 9 percent of the observed increase in tractor adoption and 28 
 percent of the decline in the agricultural employment share between 1940 a
 nd 1954.\n\nContact: Cristiano Mantovani & Aniket Baksy (cristiano.mantova
 ni@unimelb.edu.au\; aniket.baksy@unimelb.edu.au)
URL:https://fbe.unimelb.edu.au/economics/events/macro/macroeconomics-semin
 ar-series-terry-cheung-academia-sinica
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Economic Theory Seminar Series - Joshua Gans (University of Toront
 o)
DTSTART:20260220T110000
DTEND:20260220T121500
DESCRIPTION:Title: Price Discrimination with Costless Resale\n\nAbstract: 
 This paper shows that income effects create an endogenous barrier to arbit
 rage\, allowing price discrimination to survive costless resale. A monopol
 ist sells an indivisible good to consumers with heterogeneous incomes who 
 can freely resell. When the good is strictly normal\, a consumer’s reser
 vation price to resell increases as the purchase price decreases—lower p
 rices leave buyers wealthier and raise their valuation of the good. The mo
 nopolist exploits this by subsidising low-income consumers to raise their 
 reservation prices to a target that high-income consumers must also pay. T
 he optimal schedule increases dollar-for-dollar with income in the subsidi
 sed segment\, weakly dominates uniform pricing\, and achieves the first-be
 st allocation when the entire market is served. We show the mechanism exte
 nds beyond income effects: low substitutability with market alternatives g
 enerates large reservation-price responses even when income sensitivity is
  modest. Sustaining discrimination requires market power at the individual
  level—consumer-specific quantity limits—not merely aggregate output r
 estrictions. Extensions examine multiple monopolists and endogenous privac
 y choices.\n\nContact: Georgy Artemov (georgy.artemov@unimelb.edu.au)
URL:https://fbe.unimelb.edu.au/economics/events/ecotheory/economic-theory-
 seminar-series-joshua-gans-university-of-toronto
END:VEVENT
END:VCALENDAR
